<figure
  class="hamjepa-concept-diagram"
  aria-labelledby="hamjepa-predictor-gap-title"
  aria-describedby="hamjepa-predictor-gap-caption"
>
  <div class="hamjepa-concept-scroll" tabindex="0" aria-label="Scrollable predictor-versus-collapse diagram">
    <svg
      class="hamjepa-concept-svg"
      viewBox="0 0 1080 720"
      role="img"
      aria-labelledby="hamjepa-predictor-gap-title hamjepa-predictor-gap-desc"
      preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet"
    >
      <title id="hamjepa-predictor-gap-title">Why the predictor alone is not enough</title>
      <desc id="hamjepa-predictor-gap-desc">
        Stacked causal flow: many different views go through E-theta, collapse into a low-volume state cloud, then
        pass through a symplectic predictor and remain low-volume.
      </desc>

      <defs>
        <marker id="ham-gap-arrow" markerWidth="9" markerHeight="9" refX="7.4" refY="4.5" orient="auto">
          <path d="M0,0 L9,4.5 L0,9 z" fill="#4d5866" />
        </marker>
      </defs>

      <text x="230" y="62" class="t-head" text-anchor="middle">many different views</text>
      <rect x="70" y="94" width="320" height="158" rx="14" class="panel panel-a" />
      <rect x="102" y="126" width="58" height="42" rx="7" class="tiny-view" />
      <rect x="154" y="112" width="58" height="42" rx="7" class="tiny-view" />
      <rect x="208" y="132" width="58" height="42" rx="7" class="tiny-view" />
      <rect x="262" y="116" width="58" height="42" rx="7" class="tiny-view" />
      <rect x="126" y="178" width="58" height="42" rx="7" class="tiny-view" />
      <rect x="182" y="172" width="58" height="42" rx="7" class="tiny-view" />
      <rect x="238" y="186" width="58" height="42" rx="7" class="tiny-view" />

      <text x="822" y="62" class="t-head" text-anchor="middle">shared encoder</text>
      <rect x="684" y="98" width="276" height="126" rx="14" class="encoder-box" />
      <text x="822" y="174" class="t-math" text-anchor="middle">E<tspan baseline-shift="sub" font-size="70%">θ</tspan></text>

      <text x="540" y="314" class="t-head" text-anchor="middle">collapsed states</text>
      <rect x="360" y="344" width="360" height="150" rx="14" class="panel panel-b" />
      <ellipse cx="540" cy="420" rx="60" ry="14" class="collapsed-shape" />
      <circle cx="524" cy="414" r="11" class="collapsed-dot" />
      <circle cx="540" cy="420" r="11" class="collapsed-dot" />
      <circle cx="556" cy="416" r="11" class="collapsed-dot" />
      <circle cx="550" cy="428" r="10" class="collapsed-dot" />
      <circle cx="532" cy="426" r="10" class="collapsed-dot" />

      <text x="822" y="522" class="t-head" text-anchor="middle">symplectic predictor</text>
      <rect x="684" y="548" width="276" height="92" rx="12" class="predictor-box" />
      <text x="822" y="604" class="t-math-pred" text-anchor="middle">
        Φ<tspan baseline-shift="sub" font-size="70%">φ</tspan><tspan baseline-shift="super" font-size="70%">(K)</tspan>
      </text>

      <text x="244" y="522" class="t-head" text-anchor="middle">still low-volume</text>
      <rect x="84" y="548" width="320" height="92" rx="12" class="panel panel-c" />
      <ellipse cx="244" cy="594" rx="110" ry="16" class="low-volume-shape" />

      <line x1="390" y1="172" x2="684" y2="172" class="a-main" marker-end="url(#ham-gap-arrow)" />
      <line x1="822" y1="224" x2="600" y2="344" class="a-main" marker-end="url(#ham-gap-arrow)" />
      <line x1="624" y1="494" x2="762" y2="548" class="a-main" marker-end="url(#ham-gap-arrow)" />
      <line x1="684" y1="594" x2="404" y2="594" class="a-main" marker-end="url(#ham-gap-arrow)" />
    </svg>
  </div>

  <figcaption id="hamjepa-predictor-gap-caption" class="hamjepa-concept-caption">
    <strong>Why the predictor alone is not enough.</strong> Even if the predictor is perfectly symplectic, the encoder
    could still map many different views to nearly the same latent state. In that situation the rollout acts on an
    already-collapsed representation. This is why HamJEPA needs a second component beyond the predictor: encoder-side
    anti-collapse regularization.
  </figcaption>
</figure>

